      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 15-year-old girl presents to the pediatric outpatient department with progressive writhing and jerking movements of the extremities, excessive drooling, and multiple joint pains. On examination, a brown-yellow pigment is noted around the iris. Despite an unremarkable CT scan, an MRI reveals bilateral hypodense areas in the basal ganglia. Laboratory tests show elevated levels of aspartate transaminase (AST) and alanine transaminase (ALT). Based on the clinical presentation and investigative findings, which gene is most likely responsible for her condition?</span></span></span></p>",
